<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Implements New Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401163994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1442 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin has brought into 
force the new program of privatization of state and municipal 
enterprises which is to regulate the privatization process in 
Russia beginning in 1994. 
  The approved state program does not greatly differ from the 
privatization program which was in effect in 1992-1993. The new 
program does not change the major peculiarity of the Russian 
legislature on privatization, namely privatization by means of 
vouchers; their term of operation is to expire on July 1, 1994. 
  In comparison with the previous one, the new state program 
expands rights of the regions and increases the list of sites, 
the privatization of which was earlier prohibited or restricted. 
  In addition, this document removes all restrictions for the 
participation of foreign investors in the privatization of 
Russian state property. According to the state program, foreign 
individuals and legal entities can participate in auctions and 
competitions organized to sell state property on equal rights 
with Russian investors. Foreign investors are allowed to 
procure state securities (including vouchers) without any 
coordination with the RF [Russian Federation] Finance Ministry 
(according to the decree on foreign investments, a foreigner had 
to receive permission from the Finance Ministry in order to buy 
state securities). 
  Chairman of Russia's State Property committee Dmitriy 
Vasilyev says that about 80% of state property is expected to be 
privatized by July 1, 1994. Currently, 45-50% of Russian 
property belongs to the private sector. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

