<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Mafia-Like Structures' Blamed for Ruble Banknote Rumors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401173794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1603 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ruslan Maysigov] </F>
  [Text] Nazran January 4 TASS -- The new year has brought 
new problems into the Republic of Ingushetia where shops and 
everyday service facilities refuse to accept 50,000 rouble 
banknotes from their clients under various pretexts. 
  The republic has been lately swept by rumours about an 
upcoming money reform in Russia. Having learnt the bitter 
lesson of previous money reforms, workers and employees of state 
organisations and enterprises also refuse to take their salaries 
in 50,000 rouble notes. Earlier such rumours rattled the 
neighbouring Chechen Republic. 
  Meanwhile, black marketeers and shadow economy dealers are 
buying up the rejected bills for 45,000 roubles in banknotes of 
10,000 and 5,000 rouble denomination. 
  abdul-Khamid Aushev, a Russian Central Bank representative 
in 
Ingushetia, said that "such rumours are being spread by 
mafia-like structures and hard currency dealers for their own 
benefit." Aushev said he had contacted the Central Bank which 
had denied these rumours as groundless. 

</TEXT>

