<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Plans To Double Arms Trade in 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2812151393 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1452 GMT 28 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD2812151393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Business-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow December 28 TASS -- Russia has good chances 
to double its exports of military equipment in 1994 thanks to 
the work in the past two years which can result in major 
contracts, according to Foreign Trade Minister Oleg Davydov. 
  According to experts of his ministry, Russia exported 
armaments worth 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1993. 
  A major contract on shipments of MiG-29 fighter planes to 
Malaysia is expected early next year, Davydov told Business-TASS 
on Tuesday. 
  The minister denied allegations that Russia had sustained 
considerable losses by ceasing military shipments to former 
Soviet allies as those were mostly free of charge deliveries. 
  "for political reasons we have stopped arms shipments to a 
number of warring countries - Afghanistan, Angola, Ethiopia and 
others. But Russia did not practically earn any money from that. 
Now the arms trade is going on only for hard currency", Davydov 
said. 
  The minister hopes the creation of the "Rosvooruzhenie" 
company which is to unite major Russian military exporters will 
open new prospects for arms trade. 
  He added that his ministry retains the licencing right, will 
draft intergovernmental agreements and carry out export control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

