<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   MiG Builders Divert Into Light Plane Production </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0401162194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 23 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0401162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Aleksandr Galkin and Sergey Vikulin; from the "Novosti" </F>
newscast] 
  [Excerpts] [Galkin over video of MiG assembly hall] This 
is the Moscow Aviation Production Association named for 
Dementyev. It is marking its centennial today. It all began 
with the "Duks" bicycle. [passage omitted] 
  Later the "Duks" plant became the "Znamya Truda," working 
exclusively for military aviation during the past decades and 
achieving unique productivity and quality. 
  However, perestroyka, together with a wrongly understood 
theory of conversion, almost made the plant lose its aviation 
specialization. Strange as it may seem, this giant plant was 
saved by the "Aviatika" light biplane, which is being assembled 
in the same premises as the awesome MiG-29. [passage omitted] 
  It has to be admitted that the Russian Government has not 
ordered a single aircraft yet. However, it seems that abroad 
demand for our aircraft equipment is growing. Although this 
path has its problems too. 

</TEXT>

