<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry's Poverty Jeopardizes Military Production </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501100194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 2100 GMT 28 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mikhail Zotov and Valeriy Rekuta from Moscow Radio </F>
Technical Plant; from the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] [Zotov] This half-empty hall once housed a unit for 
the installation of electronics in missiles. Now Grundig color 
television sets are being assembled here in a remote corner. 
And although the Moscow Radio Technical Plant still does not 
have a signboard, this once-secret military facility is not 
secret any more. 
  In the kingdom of defense agencies everything is topsy-turvy 
nowadays. More than 70 percent of the plant's output consists 
of civilian goods and only 30 percent is military output. The 
military output includes the renowned electronics for the 
super-modern air defense missile complexes which are superior to 
Western counterparts. 
  Incidentally, the plant, which is now a leasehold 
enterprise, 
could end the production of all military output without any 
financial or legal liability even if this were to the detriment 
of the country's defense capability. After all, there is still 
no law on state orders. There are other reasons, too. So, for 
example the plant received nothing from the sale to China of 
several air defense systems apart from down-filled jackets and 
some bedding which the workers immediately dubbed "foot cloths." 
  [M. Milovanov, Moscow Radio Technical Plant general 
director, 
identified by caption] We want to survive and we are doing our 
utmost to ensure that we do. The plant management is constantly 
in an impossible situation as a result of Defense Ministry 
defaulting on payments; 1993 is drawing to a close and we are 
still owed 7.352 billion rubles [R]. We in turn owe our 
suppliers R1.5 billion. 
  [Zotov] The work force of this plant, which posseses unique 
military technologies, is barely managing to get by thanks to 
the production of own "Yunost" color television sets and the 
assembly of German TV sets. It could be that they will usher in 
the next New Year minus missile complexes, but in down-filled 
jackets and with Grundig television sets. [Video shows interior, 
exterior of plant, TV set assembly, missile complexes being 
assembled and tested, interview with director, more footage of 
production facilities.] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

