<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Opposes Dual Citizenship Idea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0401103094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 4 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0401103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Albert Musin report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric: </F>
"Uzbekistan"] 
  [Excerpts] In the two days of its deliberations, the 
Supreme Soviet session has considered over 40 matters, including 
20 draft laws. [passage omitted] 
  As key news agencies have already reported, President 
Karimov 
vehemently opposed the introduction of dual citizenship in 
Uzbekistan, citing the need to make sure that all Uzbekistan 
citizens retain "the feeling of patriotism." Karimov suggested 
that Russia "not interfere in Uzbekistan's internal affairs." 
Undoubtedly, what he meant by this was Andrey Kozyrev's trip to 
Tashkent in November, when the Russian Foreign Ministry chief 
raised the question of ethnic Russians' assuming dual 
citizenship as a measure designed to prevent their mass 
migration from Uzbekistan. 
  Even before starting official talks with Kozyrev, the 
Uzbekistan president took the Russian ambassador to Tashkent to 
task in front of journalists, saying that he "will have to 
answer" for "raising the specious problem of the 
Russian-speaking population in Uzbekistan." Later, the 
journalists who rushed to the Russian Embassy saw a line of 700 
people craving to obtain Russian citizenship and leave 
Uzbekistan... 
  Also on the agenda were matters of the state budget and the 
socioeconomic situation in Uzbekistan, although they were barely 
touched. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

