<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials To Seek IMF Aid in Washington </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0401205094 Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service in 
Armenian 1630 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0401205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Economy Minister Armen Darbinyan has reported 
plans for Economy Minister Armen Yegiazaryan and First Deputy 
Foreign Minister Zhirair Liparityan to visit Washington. They 
will visit the IMF to hold talks on economic cooperation and 
will provide detailed information to the Fund's directors on the 
latest political developments. 
  Armenia has long been conducting talks with the IMF but the 
situation in the region means the IMF thinks it is inappropriate 
to allocate money to Armenia and Azerbaijan out of the 
stabilization fund for countries moving toward independence; the 
argument is that the resources could be directly or indirectly 
used for nonpeaceful purposes. 
  To dispel such an opinion, the Armenian president recently 
wrote to IMF Managing Director Camdessus expressing the hope 
that the IMF will soften its stance since Armenia is not a 
warring side and the international community has not recognized 
it as such. 
  Once in Washington, the Armenian delegation will reiterate 
our country's position, that is, to help in every way to 
establish peace in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

