<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Retreat, Surrender Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401143794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1312 
GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 4 Jan -- Fighting is continuing in the north 
and northeast of Nagorno-Karabakh. The ITAR-TASS correspondent 
was told today by the department of press and information of the 
Nagorno-Karabakh Republic [NKR] that on Monday evening subunits 
of the Azerbaijani Army, which had gone on the offensive, were 
forced to retreat to their original positions after losing two 
armored vehicles and with around 90 soldiers and officers 
killed. Five soldiers were killed and 13 injured on the 
Karabakh side. 
  According to a report from the news service of the NKR 
defense army, instances of Azerbaijani servicemen voluntarily 
giving themselves up as prisoners have increased. Fourteen 
people have done this over the past two weeks. The prisoners 
say that they are being forced into this because they are 
frightened of being shot by mine-laying detachments coming from 
behind. Among the soldiers in the mine-laying detachments are 
Afghan mojahedin and the fact of their involvement in the 
Karabakh war on the Azerbaijani side is admitted by both 
military experts and independent observers. 
  According to the NKR State Committee for Defense, there are 
more than 40 seized documents in Stepanakert that show that 
around 1,500 Afghan mojahedin are involved in the conflict on 
the Azerbaijani side. They came to Azerbaijan as far back as 
July last year. The mojahedin's subunits are also suffering 
losses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

