<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patsatsiya Voices Peace Hopes for South Ossetia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401141094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian Prime Minister Otar Patsatsiya expressed 
hope that the Georgian-Ossetian conflict would be entirely 
settled this year and tens of thousands of refugees would be 
able to return to their homes in South Ossetia. The premier 
voiced this statement in the village of Tamaresheni in South 
Ossetia, which he visited on January 3. 
  The press center of the Georgian government reported to 
Interfax that the premier had a meeting with the command of the 
Russian and Ossetian peacekeeping battalions on the territory of 
the Russian military unit not far from Tskhinvali, an 
administrative center in South Ossetia. Since July 1992, these 
battalions have been overseeing the cease-fire in this region 
together with Georgian servicemen. 
  Patsatsiya also visited several Georgian villages in South 
Ossetia where he promised the local population to provide them 
with food products and other necessary consumer goods. 
  The Georgian-Ossetian conflict began in January 1991 as a 
result of Georgian forces introduced into South Ossetia after 
the South Ossetian leadership declared its intention to raise 
the status of South Ossetia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

