<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Special Situation Regime' Tightened in Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401174694 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1600 GMT 
4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The special situation regime has been tightened 
throughout the territory of Abkhazia. The reason is that during 
the post-war period a lot of time has been spent on setting up 
law enforcement bodies and strengthening them with 
professionals, time which has been used by criminal elements. 
By the end of 1993, a RIA correspondent was told by Konstantin 
Adleber, chief of staff of the Abkhazian MVD [Ministry of 
Internal Affairs] Headquarters, that the number of particularly 
serious crimes has been considerably reduced. Those who violate 
the curfew are now subjected to a fine of 5,000 rubles or 
detained for 3-15 hours. No military servicemen or other 
persons carrying weapons are allowed on the streets. The sale 
of spirits has been banned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

