<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tbilisi Plant, Moscow Designers Cooperate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501101594 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 2100 GMT 28 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Georgiy Ratishvili and Georgiy Bazadze; from the </F>
"Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text][Ratishvili over video of new aircraft on tarmac] 
The Tbilisi Aviation Production Association together with the 
Yakovlev Design Bureau have built a new-generation six-seater 
passenger plane -- the Yak-58. It is designed for executive and 
business flights but can be reequipped, without special 
additional expenditure, to function as an air ambulance or 
training or cargo plane. Its short takeoff and landing means 
that it can be used on improvised grass airstrips. 
  The creation of this aircraft marks the revival of mutually 
advantageous economic relations between the two states. A few 
days ago at the test range the new aircraft took off with 
enviable ease and reaching the required height successfully 
passed its first test. Present at the test range were head of 
the Georgian state Eduard Shevardnadze, Prime Minister Otar 
Patsatsia, and Georgian and foreign journalists. 

</TEXT>

