<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501064694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0629 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501064694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga January 5 TASS -- Latvia accepted the Russian 
concession that Moscow withdraws its troops from the Baltic 
republic before this September, but hinted it is not going to 
meet in full the Russian demand about keeping the radar in the 
settlement of Skrunda for another six years. 
  The republican government met on Tuesday and accepted the 
Russian proposal made two months ago that the end of August 1994 
should be the deadline for the pullout. 
  Russia which initialy wanted to complete the withdrawal by 
the end of 1994 agreed to speed it up on condition that the 
radar in Skrunda is kept for another six years. 
  Latvian Foreign Minister Georgs Andreyevs said his country 
is 
advancing a compromise decision on the radar which does not ruin 
the Russian proposal. 
  According to him, the dismantling of one of the units of the 
radar can begin immediately, however, the station will be able 
to continue working. 
  The minister refused to disclose other details saying that 
this compromise will be offered to Russia at the new round of 
talks the date of which had not been determined yet. Initially 
it was scheduled for December 20, but was suspended because of 
Russian elections. 
  He said that many foreign countries are ready to monitor the 
future agreement on the radar station. 
  However, Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis said in a TV 
interview that "no (foreign) country has yet expressed its 
position on the Skrunda (radar)." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

