<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Says New Passports Held by 50 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301170194 Tallinn BNS in English 1025 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0301170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 03, BNS -- Until the end of December 
1993, about 520,000 persons, or approximately a half of the 
citizens of Latvia have obtained new passports of the Latvian 
republic, the deputy head of the visas and passports department 
of the Latvian Interior Ministry, Janis Vidzups, told BNS. 
  At the moment, a total of 1,720,000 citizens have been 
registered in the republic. Meanwhile, the country's population 
amounts to 2,648,000 people, according to the data of 1991. 
  Vidzups said the foreign passports of the former Soviet 
Union 
will be granted to republican citizens in 1994. Only 
non-citizens residing in the republic will be able to obtain 
them. Therefore, Latvian citizens intending to travel abroad 
will have to obtain a passport of the Latvian republic. 
  The work of the visas and passports department is hampered 
by 
the fact that the Latvian parliament has not decided yet on the 
status of foreigners and aliens residing in the republic, 
Vidzups said. 
  As known, until now Latvian citizens acquiring the 
republican 
citizenship for the first time at the age of 16 years old are 
given a passport of the non-existing Soviet Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

