<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazauskas Sends Official Appeal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401203094 Vilnius Radio Vilnius in English 2000 GMT 4 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas has made an 
official appeal, asking to admit Lithuania to NATO. Speaking on 
Lithuanian television on Tuesday, the president said he had sent 
a letter to Secretary General of NATO Mr. Manfred Woerner, by 
which, taking into account a parliamentary resolution, he had 
officially appealed to admit Lithuania to the North Atlantic 
Treaty Organization. 
  In his letter, Mr Algirdas Brazauskas expressed hope that 
the 
NATO summit, due January 10 through 11, would open possibilities 
for the central and east European states to join that 
organization. The president said Lithuania's standpoint toward 
its membership in NATO was not aimed at confrontation with 
either the neighboring countries or any other European state. 
  Lately the right-wing opposition has been criticizing the 
Lithuanian president and the governing Democratic Labor Party 
for too irresolute a position toward Lithuanian membership in 
NATO. 
  Meanwhile, the leader of the right-wing opposition, Mr. 
Vytautas Landsbergis, has expressed hope that the letter of the 
Lithuanian president to the NATO secretary general will attract 
attention in the West. As the opposition leader put it, then 
Lithuania will stand side by side with Poland, not only on the 
map of Europe, but also on the list of candidates for membership 
in NATO. 
  Mr. Landsbergis on Tuesday made a statement falling in line 
with that by the president, that Lithuania is seeking stability 
and protection, and that this, in his words, is not a threat or 
humiliation for anybody. 
  The opposition leader said Lithuania's desire to join NATO 
did not run counter to the U.S. partnership for peace initiative. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

