<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Landsbergis on Yeltsin, NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301205194 Tallinn BNS in English 1525 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0301205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 03, BNS -- "I wish there would be no 
new Yalta" conference this year, said Vytautas Landsbergis, 
leader of the parliament's rightist opposition. 
  At a press conference Monday, Landsbergis said signs of a 
"new Yalta" have appeared and are very threatening to central 
Europe, especially Lithuania. 
  Discussing the problem of NATO membership, the opposition 
leader said a decision to join the alliance is 
"self-determination, and not only for countries in our region, 
but for western countries, as well." 
  Landsbergis said Bulgaria and Macedonia have already 
officially asked for NATO membership and are treated as "the 
last states to have expressed a wish" to join the alliance. He 
expressed hope that Lithuania will be "the last one" and the 
Dec. 23 resolution of the Lithuanian parliament will be taken 
into account. 
  Meanwhile, the Lithuanian administration simply awaits the 
Jan. 10 NATO summit, the opposition leader said. He reminded 
reporters that Lithuanian authorities still have several days 
left to make their move. 
  Landsbergis said he is deeply concerned about a New Year's 
speech by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who vowed to better 
defend the interests of Russians living in the former Soviet 
republics. The opposition leader pointed out Yeltsin's words 
that Russia will have difficulty in preserving peace and that 
Russia will defend its own interests, as well as the interests 
of its citizens in other countries. 

</TEXT>

