<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Motives for Lifting of Blockade on Abkhazia Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0401120094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 4 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0401120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Igor Rotar report under the "Conflict" rubric: "Economic </F>
Blockade of Abkhazia Has Been Lifted. Men in Tbilisi Abstain 
From Comment"] 
  [Text] Russia has ended its economic blockade of Abkhazia. 
As has been explained to your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent 
at the Russian Foreign Ministry CIS Department, Moscow's 
decision is the result of the following considerations: The 
leaders of Abkhazia have been of late demonstrating their 
readiness for a dialogue with Tbilisi and taking specific steps 
toward a peaceful settlement of the situation in the conflict 
zone. Besides, it is primarily civilians, including Russians, 
who are suffering from the blockade. In the opinion of Russian 
diplomats, the lifting of the blockade shortly before the new 
year will be assessed as Moscow's goodwill gesture and will 
contribute to the stabilization of the situation in the region. 
  From the point of view of Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba, 
Russia's blockade of Abkhazia contravened the Geneva agreement 
signed by Moscow. (One of the items in the document says: "The 
sides appeal to the international community for assistance in 
restoring the life-support systems in the zone of conflict....") 
  The problem, however, has a reverse side too. Russia, as a 
guarantor of the Sochi agreement, is responsible for any 
violation of the understandings by the Abkhaz side. 
Significantly, in his interview for your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 
correspondent, Andrey Kozyrev did not deny facts attesting to 
Russian Army help to the Abkhaz people. The blockade of 
Abkhazia demonstrated to the world community, albeit not too 
convincingly, that Moscow condemned the violators of the Sochi 
agreement. The lifting of the blockade in effect consolidates 
the victory for Abkhaz military formations and, as a 
consequence, will lead to even an greater anti-Russian mood in 
Georgia. True, at this stage, as your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 
correspondent was told at the Georgian Embassy, Tbilisi 
officials refrain from assessing the event. 
  Also rather interesting is the fact that Moscow has made up 
its mind to lift the blockade despite the fact that there was 
after all no real progress in the settlement of the Abkhaz 
crisis. NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA has already reported (21 December 
1993) that the problem of refugees from Abkhazia had been the 
main stumbling block in the talks between Tbilisi and Gudauta: 
the Abkhaz side insists that the republic's status be 
determined in a referendum. Today, as an overwhelming majority 
of Georgians have left Abkhazia, a referendum, according to 
Tbilisi, will not be legitimate. As Vladislav Ardzinba stated 
in an interview with your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent, the 
republic's leaders today cannot guarantee the safety of Georgian 
refugees who would like to return, hence the question of the 
republic's status is being shelved once again. Also, your 
NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent, who has just returned from 
Abkhazia, can testify that the remaining Georgian population in 
the republic is continuing to be plundered. 
  Moscow's position would have been explicable had it rejected 
the blockade idea right away on the grounds that it was 
unwilling to punish innocent civilians. As for Moscow's present 
decision, there may be only two explanations: Either Russia has 
realized it made yet another mistake, or the decision to 
institute economic sanctions had been no more than a trick aimed 
at pacifying the world community. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

