<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin, Armenia's Bagratyan Hold Closed Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401210794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1925 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401210794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A closed meeting of Russian and Armenian delegations 
headed by Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and his 
Armenian counterpart, Grant Bagratyan, was held in the 
government building on the Krasnopresnenskaya embankment today. 
  Armenian Ambassador to Russia Feliks Mamikoniyan, who also 
took part in the negotiations, told Interfax that the meeting 
focused on a package of agreements which had been meant to be 
agreed on rather than signed. "As a result, the differences 
between the Russian and Armenian sides were settled," the 
diplomat pointed out. Mamikoniyan stressed that "Armenia did not 
take the role of an supplicant; it was a tough, but good-natured 
talk between two partners, each with its own capabilities." 
  Commenting on the draft bilateral trade and economic 
agreement for 1994, Mamikoniyan said "a mechanism for settling 
differences was found." The ambassador added that the 
differences were over Yerevan's settlements of payments for 
Russian clearing deliveries of goods. He said "Armenia has 
funds to pay, but the country finds itself in a transportation 
blockade." 
  According to Mamikoniyan, the Russian prime minister spoke 
against the proposal by the Russian concern "Roskontrakt" to 
transform Armenia's debt for Russian oil worth 40 billion rubles 
into Russia's state debt and enable this commercial organization 
to independently look for ways to settle the payments issue with 
its partners. 
  Mamikoniyan said the Russian side treated with understanding 
the request to grant a humanitarian credit worth 10 billion 
rubles to Armenia to enable it to reconstruct the facilities in 
the area hit by an earthquake in December 1998. The meeting 
also discussed granting 23 out of 40 billion rubles of the 
Russian state credit to Armenia in 1993 that have never been 
used. 
  According to Mamikoniyan, Yerevan proposed setting up a 
joint 
venture with Russia to exploit the Armenian nuclear power 
station which is now under reconditioning and prepared for 
launch. The two sides agreed to prepare a draft 
intergovernmental agreement on the issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

