<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Workers `Helping To Pay Vietnam's Debts' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0401145194 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2000 GMT 23 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0401145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Vietnam by V. Konnov; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Konnov] A great deal has changed, both in our 
own country and in the countries of the former socialist camp. 
The stormy debate about who owes whom more has subsided. The 
bombastic statements about proletarian internationalism and 
fraternal assistance have disappeared. What remains is business 
as usual. In this respect the Vietsovpetro Russian-Vietnamese 
joint venture has stood the test of time. Established a decade 
ago, it produced its first oil in 1986. And recently workers 
were being congratulated in the terse language of posters on the 
achievement of having extracted 20 million tonnes of oil. The 
banner slogans may look somewhat naive and old-fashioned today, 
but they must not obscure the main point: An entire community 
of Russian oil workers is living and working in the south of 
Vietnam. Oil extraction is helping to pay Vietnam's debts. And 
yields are rising. 
  A new floating rig is being readied for dispatch here. It is 
intended for the White Dragon deposit -- the richest oil deposit 
on Vietnam's south coast. 

</TEXT>

