<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijanis Reportedly Sustaining Losses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0401163194 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1400 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0401163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1400 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Azerbaijani Army formations have been sustaining 
enormous losses in their incessant attacks on Karabakh defensive 
positions for the past three weeks. 
  The Nagorno-Karabakh Republic Defense Army Press Service 
reported that heavy fighting continued on the north and 
northeast fronts on the evening of 3 January. After losing one 
tank, one infantry fighting vehicle, and 90 soldiers and 
officers, the enemy retreated to its initial positions. Five 
fighters were killed and 13 wounded on the Karabakh side. The 
fighting has continued in these sectors since this morning. 
  The same source says Azerbaijani soldiers frequently 
surrender. Four gave themselves up on 3 January alone and 14 
have surrendered over the past three weeks. They confessed to 
being forced to fight fearing execution by the so-called 
deterrent detachments, which stay behind the Army formations. 
According to the prisoners, the deterrent detachments are 
basically formed of Afghan mojahedin because the Azerbaijanis 
themselves refuse to fire on their own soldiers. 
  Friends, for many days now we have been unable--through no 
fault of our own--to report on the situation in the border 
regions of the Republic. Telephone links have been disrupted 
preventing us from receiving reports from the Defense Ministry's 
press service. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

