<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Doubts Remain on Resolving Nuclear Issue at Moscow Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501183094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1616 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: reports by </F>
Diplomatic Correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoi and others] 
  [Text] During a three-sided meeting of the presidents of 
Russia, Ukraine and the United States in Moscow, not all issues, 
if any, concerning nuclear weapons in Ukraine are likely to be 
cleared up. The only thing Leonid Kravchuk of Ukraine can do is 
to confirm unambiguously to Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton his 
republic's international commitments on nuclear disarmament and 
promise to submit again the START-I treaty for ratification by 
the new parliament. 
  This statement was made to INTERFAX Wednesday by a senior 
Russian diplomat responsible for Russian-Ukrainian relations. 
  He believes that the likely three-sided summit may present a 
good opportunity for Kravchuk to distance himself in public from 
the partial ratification of the treaty. 
  The diplomat has said the United States promised to Ukraine 
financial aid worth $170 Mn [Million] as soon as the disarmament 
process begins. 
  The Americans are practically-minded people. They will not 
give money to Ukraine for mere promises, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

