<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Preparing Ministry Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501170994 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1540 GMT 
5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zurab Dvalia, IPRINDA news agency correspondent, 
reports from Georgia by telephone. 
  [Dvalia] A constituent meeting of the Abkhazian regional 
branch of the Union of Georgian Citizens took place in Tbilisi 
today. The union is headed by Eduard Shevardnadze. The 
speakers noted the need to unite all forces in order to attain 
stability and order in the republic. Head of State Eduard 
Shevardnadze himself spoke at the meeting. He gave a brief 
analysis of the sociopolitical situation that had taken shape. 
Naturally, he paid special attention to the Abkhazian problem. 
For the first time over the few months since Georgian troops 
had left Abkhazia, Shevardnadze openly said that, apart from 
everything else, a large-scale betrayal near the Katorskiy 
bridge in Abkhazia was one of the main reasons for the defeat in 
Abkhazia. Also, this betrayal took place in Ochamchira Rayon, 
as well as in Sukhumi, where whole battalions were often 
withdrawn from advanced positions without command agreement. 
  Shevardnadze openly accused Tengiz Kitovani, former 
republican defense minister, and General Paata Datunashvili, 
current first deputy defense minister, of handing over great 
amounts of weapons, ammunition, and hardware to the armed 
formations of the ex- president's supporters. 
  The head of state noted that today's Georgia did not have, 
in 
fact, a unified disciplined army since the available armed 
forces cannot be regarded as such. Also, he said that in the 
next few days he intended to issue several decrees aimed at 
forming new unified armed forces but he did not elaborate on the 
subject. 
  At the same time, it has become known from unofficial 
sources 
that serious changes are being prepared in the top echelons of 
the Georgian Defense Ministry. 

</TEXT>

