<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Holds Talks With Senators Nunn, Lugar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Concerned Over DPRK </H4>
<F P=102> LD0501173294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has voiced 
concern over North Korea's possible withdrawal from the nuclear 
nonproliferation treaty [NPT]. Meeting U.S. senators Sam Nunn 
and Richard Lugar Wednesday [5 January], he said that the step 
by the North Korean leadership could deteriorate the situation 
not only on the Korean Peninsula, but the world over. 
  Pyongyang declared its intention to withdraw from the 
nuclear 
nonproliferation treaty in March 1993. Grachev said Russia 
favors further inter-Korean dialogue. The minister described as 
counterproductive the possibility to impose international 
sanctions against North Korea. The problem should not be 
tackled with hastiness. He believes it is necessary to consider 
the possible political and military implications that could 
follow the sanctions, as well as to ask for China's opinion on 
the issue, since the country has very close contacts with North 
Korea. 
  The minister has said that Russia stands for a balanced 
approach to the issue. He also believes that the international 
impact on Pyongyang should be aimed at drawing North Korea to 
rejoin the treaty, not at expanding its isolation. The 
development of the North Korean-U.S. talks, he believes, could 
be an effective means of influence. Russia and China could also 
influence Pyongyang. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55135 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov004_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-004 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Holds Talks With Senators Nunn, Lugar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Comments on NATO </H4>
<F P=102> LD0501175194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told 
American senators Sam Nunn and Richard Lugar on Wednesday [5 
January] that he favored broader cooperation with NATO. He 
noted, however, that NATO's concept - partnership for peace - 
should take into account the interests of all states, not only 
the NATO members. 
  Grachev believes that this concept should apply not only to 
NATO, but also to the all-European security system and said that 
Russia was ready to develop cooperation with NATO on the basis 
of the following principles: the development of general 
political contacts, coordination of positions, and practical and 
coordinated actions. 
  Commenting on the basic principles of Russia's military 
doctrine at the senators' request, Grachev stated that this 
document was political rather than military, and that the 
renunciation of the principle not to use nuclear weapons first 
puts it on a par with similar documents on other nuclear powers. 
  Russia views nuclear weapons as a deterrent, not as a means 
of warfare, he said. He noted in this connection that the 
commitment not to use nuclear weapons first was at variance with 
this assumption. 
  He expressed the opinion that this commitment had not been 
taken seriously by the west. It was viewed simply as a 
propaganda statement undermining the former Soviet Union's 
military policy, said Grachev. He remarked, however, that the 
former Soviet Union had no plans to deal preemptive nuclear 
blows on any country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55136 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov004_a_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-004 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

