<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Reinforces Blue Helmets on Croatian Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601110394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1038 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- 305 Russian paratroopers 
with weapons and equipment left late on Wednesday [5 January] to 
reinforce the Russian battalion of "blue helmets" ensuring peace 
on the border between Krajina Serb and Croatia. 
  It is for the first time that the Russian peace-keepers will 
be armed with mortars, anti-tank missiles and anti-aircraft 
weapons. Earlier the Russian soldiers had only firearms with 
them. 
  The service of the Russian airborne troops told TASS on 
Thursday that the paratroopers were dispatched upon a request of 
the commander of the UN peace-keeping forces in former 
Yugoslavia and with the knowledge of the UN Security Council. 
  It added that it is hard for the current strength of the 
Russian battalion to fulfil its mission on the border between 
Krajina Serb and Croatia. The zone monitored by the Russian 
force is 100 kilometres long and 30 kilometres wide and has 24 
checkpoints. 
  Both Croats and Serbs regularly violate ceasefire there. 
  The train with paratroopers is expected to arrive in place 
on 
January 9. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

