<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, Belarus To Merge Monetary Systems Mid-Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501180194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1723 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 5 TASS -- Russia and Belarus agreed 
on Wednesday [5 January] to merge their monetary systems as of 
mid-January, 1994 and make the Russian rouble the only legal 
tender in both republics. 
  The decision was reached during the Russian-Belarusian talks 
in Moscow which were attended by Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Belarusian 
Premier Vyacheslav Kebich. 
  The participants signed a joint statement on the integration 
of the Russian and Belarusian monetary systems. The statement 
said that the integration will take place after the prime 
ministers of the two republics have signed a package of more 
than ten agreements specifying the mechanism of integration in 
Minsk in the second half of January. 
  Kebich told ITAR-TASS after the three-hour talks that the 
sides have also agreed the exchange rate of the Russian rouble 
and the Belarusian coupon under which one coupon will be 
exchanged for one rouble. 
  Kebich also said that Yeltsin expressed the hope that the 
agreements to be signed in Minsk will come into force as soon as 
possible. "This would fully meet the interests of the heads of 
government," he added. 
  The Belarusian premier believes that the process of 
Belarus's 
transition to the Russian rouble will be long and may take three 
to six months. This is caused mostly by technical problems of 
cash supplies to Belarus. Kebich said some other CIS states may 
also join the rouble zone. "But for this to happen, a certain 
mechanism should be worked out," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

