<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin on Closer Economic Ties With Belarus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501205294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2024 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 5 TASS -- "A statement signed by the 
heads of the Russian and Belarusian governments in Moscow today 
on the merger of the monetary systems of the two countries is an 
important landmark we sought to achieve," said Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin during a brief conversation with 
journalists after the ceremony of signing the document was over. 
  The Russian prime minister pointed out in reply to a 
question asked by ITAR-TASS that "today, Russia and Belarus have 
not only come up close to the merger of their monetary systems, 
but to the deepening of economic integration in the CIS 
framework." 
  Chernomyrdin pointed out that the creation of the single 
rouble space between the two countries has a mutually 
advantageous character, adding that "none of us is seeking to 
gain any advantage at each other's expense". The prime minister 
declared that "by signing today's statement, Russia does not 
encroach on Belarusian sovereignty. The document is aimed at 
deepening the coordination of our activities in the economic 
sphere and this is the principle followed by the whole Europe in 
its development." 
  As a result of Russo-Belarusian talks held in the building 
of the Russian Government on Wednesday, Viktor Chernomyrdin and 
Vyacheslav Kebich signed an agreement on trade and economic 
cooperation in 1994. Vice-premiers of the two countries, 
Aleksandr Shokhin and Vladimir Zalomay, signed an agreement on 
supplies of Russian natural gas to Belarus and the construction 
of a system of gas pipelines on the Belarusian territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

