<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on `Useful' Foreign Property Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501215494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1616 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501215494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] Aleksandr Udaltsov, a senior Russian diplomat in 
charge of relations with the Baltics, told Interfax that the 
talks Russian Deputy Foreign Ministers Boris Pastukhov and 
Sergey Krylov held Tuesday with their Lithuanian counterpart 
Albinas Januska were regarded as useful in the Russian Foreign 
Ministry. 
  Udaltsov said that the talks covered the foreign property of 
Lithuania and Russia following the disintegration of the USSR 
and issues in the functioning of the Russian embassy in Vilnius 
and the Lithuanian embassy in Moscow. 
  He emphasized that it was the first time the two sides had 
discused "this delicate matter. ...One could not expect to have 
all the property issues settled in one day. What is important 
is that we have come to an understanding of the way these issues 
should be discussed." 
  The diplomat expressed the hope that in further talks, to be 
held in Vilnius shortly, the two sides will agree on the 
Lithuanian embassy buildings in Rome and Paris that had been 
taken over by the USSR in 1940. The Lithuanians want them back. 
  Another senior Russian Foreign Ministry official, who also 
handles Baltic issues, thinks that the outlook for solution of 
the "property issue" is "dim." 
  He told Interfax that there was no solution in sight for the 
problem of the Russian embassy in Vilnius. "We would like to 
purchase good premises using the cash Lithuania owes for 
supplies of natural gas but the Lithuanian authorities remain 
ambiguous on that," he said. 
  The diplomat also said that the Lithuanian ownership rights 
of numerous buildings in Moscow "are in serious doubt." In his 
words, Lithuanian diplomats have no documents confirming their 
rights to use premises they now hold. 
  He said that Russia owned the former Lithuanian embassy 
building in Rome "quite legally" while the situation in Paris 
was "more complicated and should become the subject of bilateral 
talks, especially because French authorities refused to act as 
arbiters." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

