<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Not To Apply to NATO Individually </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501161994 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1300 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Estonia will not express in the near future an 
official wish to become a NATO member, the head of the first 
bureau of the Foreign Ministry, (Raimo Reinart), asserted to the 
BNS [BALTIC NEWS SERVICE]. In the words of the foreign ministry 
representative, all three Baltic States have already expressed 
their wish to become integrated in the security structures of 
Europe, among them NATO. In what forms one or another state 
expresses its plans is no longer that important, considered 
(Reinart) in the interview given to the BNS. He said that the 
question of Lithuania will not be discussed in Brussels 
separately, but in the joint context of central and eastern 
European states. (Reinart) emphasized that joining NATO was a 
lengthy process, in the course of which armaments, control of 
troops and many other questions would have to be generalized. 
This was enabled by the Partnership for Peace program offered 
by the United States of America, which, in the words of 
(Reinart), was supported by all three Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

