<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgiy Satarov on Revamping Administration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501203094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1528 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 5 TASS -- "Can the presidential 
administration and the Russian Government be reorganized from 
the inside, through the efforts of the apparatus, and in face of 
inside opposition? This is the problem," member of the 
Presidential Council Georgiy Satarov told ITAR-TASS here today. 
  He claims that the present state apparatus is inefficient. 
Any transition of power from elected politicians to a 
bureaucratic apparatus engenders an urge to uphold corporative 
interests, not the interests of the electorate. This leads to 
the formation of an "army of state bureaucrats" in Russia. 
  "The obviously low level of professionalism is another 
drawback of Russian bureaucracy," Satarov believes. This is why 
politicians of the "latest call-up" have "raised much fuss and 
have provoked political squabbles in the upper echelons of 
power, turning apparatus offices into party headquarters". This 
resulted in the apparatus's deep politisation which leaves it 
very little time for real work. 
  Consequently, the bureaucrats have abused the powers given 
them by the apparatus to satisfy personal political ambitions. 
The Russian people could witness this before the latest 
parliamentary elections. 
  Satarov noted that "Boris Yeltsin has realised the existence 
of this problem, and this is confirmed by his intention to 
revamp his own administration and the government by cutting the 
number of officials". Moreover, the president told a press 
conference on December 22 that it was necessary to pursue a 
publicly open policy, to promote a permanent dialogue between 
the authorities and the society." 
  Satarov believes that both these things are most important, 
as well as the personnel policy's orientation on 
professionalism, which could "reduce the share of politicised 
bureaucrats and their destructive influence". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55174 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov004_b_94012" </HT>


