<H3> <TI>   Press Service Denies Yeltsin Letter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601084894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0803 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- The press service of the 
Russian leader denied on Thursday press reports claiming that 
the Russian president had sent a personal message to former 
Soviet parliament speaker Anatoliy Lukyanov congratulating him 
on being elected to the new Russian parliament. 
  "This does not correspond to reality", the press service 
said 
and blamed the lawyer of Lukyanov, who is standing trial for 
organising the 1991 abortive Soviet coup, for misinformation. 
  The press service said that the president had sent a message 
of greetings to all the lawmakers elected to the new parliament 
in which he expressed hope for joint constructive work. 
  However, the lawyer of Lukyanov presented the message, while 
speaking in court, in such a way as if it had been sent 
personally to Lukyanov. 
  "Unfortunately, reporters failed to realise this `nuance' 
which exposes defects in professional ethics of the lawyer", the 
press service said. 

</TEXT>

