<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Guarantees Russians Freedom of Information </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501140494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0918 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 5 (ITAR-TASS) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin has decided to take additional steps to guarantee 
the right of Russian citizens to information. This is reflected 
in his "Decree on the Citizens' Right to Information", received 
by ITAR- TASS on Wednesday [5 January]. 
  The president instructed the commission for legislative 
proposals to prepare a bill "On the Right to Information", which 
would be presented to the new parliament as a top priority 
legislative initiative. 
  Until the adoption of such a law, the decree establishes the 
duty of all government bodies, organisations, enterprises, 
public associations, and responsible officials to ensure freedom 
of information. In particular, the access to information which 
is of public or personal interest to Russian citizens is 
guaranteed. 
  The decree stipulates that the essence of decisions taken by 
government bodies is to be explained more in-depth on radio and 
television programmes. The state television companies have been 
ordered to prepare a series of programmes which will explain the 
activities of federal bodies. 
  One of the decree's points particularly declares that the 
work of the legislative, executive and judicial branches of 
power are to be given equal air time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55180 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov004_b_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-004 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Edict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601095794 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0601095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The President Guarantees"] </F>
  [Text] Boris Yeltsin has decided to take additional steps 
to guarantee the right of citizens to information. This is 
served by the edict "On Additional Guarantees of the Right of 
Citizens to Information," which ITAR-TASS received yesterday. 
  The president has entrusted the Legislative Proposals 
Commission with preparing a draft law "On the Right to 
Information," which will be submitted to parliament as a 
priority legislative initiative. Pending the adoption of such a 
law, the edict establishes the responsibilities of state organs, 
organizations and enterprises, public associations, and 
officials in ensuring information openness. In particular, it 
guarantees the accessibility of information which is of public 
interest or affects citizens' personal interests. 
  The essence of state organs' decisions will be explained 
more 
extensively on radio and television. 
  One of the points in the edict particularly stipulates that 
the activities of federal organs of legislative, executive, and 
judicial power are given equal coverage in programs. 
  By means of another edict Boris Yeltsin has decided to form 
the Judicial Chamber for Information Disputes under the Russian 
Federation president on the basis of the Information Arbitration 
Court which operated during the period of preparation for the 
parliamentary elections. 
  The edict, which ITAR-TASS also received yesterday, states 
that the main functions of the Judicial Chamber are to assist 
the president in defending rights and freedoms in the mass 
information sphere; to ensure the objective and reliable nature 
of reports; to ensure the principle of equality of rights in the 
mass information sphere; to ensure protection of the moral 
interests of children and young people in the mass media; to 
ensure pluralism in news and sociopolitical television and radio 
programs; and a number of other tasks. 
  Anatoliy Vengerov has been appointed chairman of the 
Judicial 
Chamber for Information Disputes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

