<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Agreement Reached </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501173894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Party groups in the Russian State Duma have not 
reached agreement in their consultations on candidates to the 
posts of speaker and his deputies. 
  According to a well-informed source, Russia's Choice, 
Communists, Agrarians and Liberal Democrats are ready to agree 
on a speaker to represent one of the smaller groups -- 
Yavlinskiy's bloc or the Women of Russia -- on condition that 
his or her four deputies represent their four biggest groups. 
  Communists favor a strong, not decorative speaker as well as 
the formation of a leading body such as a council of the Duma. 
  According to the source, the four biggest groups are also 
discussing the formation of parliamentary committees. Russia's 
Choice is claiming leading posts in two or three (economic) 
committees, Liberal Democrats in the international affairs 
committee, Communists in defense and security committees, 
agrarians in committees on agriculture, constitutional 
legislation and legal reform. 
  A former member of the Supreme Soviet and a representative 
of 
the Agrarian Party Vladimir Isakov intends to head the latter 
committee. 

</TEXT>

