<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federal Assembly Joint Session Unlikely </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501212094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] There is every likelihood that a joint session of 
the Federal Assembly's Houses, expected in the Kremlin's Marble 
Hall on January 11, will not be convened. Most likely, the 
Federation Council and Duma will hold separate sessions on that 
day. 
  A presidential administration spokesman has told INTERFAX 
that the Federation Council and State Duma Organizing 
Committees, led by Vladimir Shumeyko and Sergey Filatov, will 
submit to Yeltsin shortly their recommendations on how 
parliamentary sessions should be held. Their guidelines will 
make up the basis of an appropriate instruction. 
  Duma is due to meet in the former building of the Mayor's 
Office on New Arbat, 36, and the Federation Council -- in the 
former Russian Press House on Bolshaya Dmitrovka, 26. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

