<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Independent Lawmakers Plan To Become Centrist Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501151894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1138 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, January 5 (TASS) -- A group of indepedent 
members of the newly-elected Russian State Duma announced on 
Wednesday that they plan to form an inter-regional association 
of independent deputies. 
  The group held a meeting in the parliamentary centre, where 
they approved a declaration about the association. The 
declaration says, "the association can and must became a true 
centre for the consolidation of all the State Duma's 
constructive forces". In the future the association intends to 
lobby for parliamentary faction status. 
  The declaration also states that the independent deputies, 
"who were elected in one-seat constituencies and are not 
obligated to any of the political parties or movements, are 
personally responsible before their voters, the constitution, 
and Russia as a whole". 
  The association promises to base its activity on "the 
principles of parliamentary freedom and responsibility, common 
sense, political realism and pragmatism, and respect for the 
views of other groups and factions". 

</TEXT>

