<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Prospective Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501224894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1725 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501224894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's meeting with 
representatives of the association of publishers and chief 
editors of the leading newspapers will be held either tonight or 
on Thursday. The agreement to hold the meeting was reached at 
the conference today of First Vice Prime Minister Vladimir 
Shumeyko, supervising the Press Ministry, with chief editors of 
the leading newspapers. 
  The meeting was attended by the chief editors of such 
newspapers as "TRUD" (Potapov), "ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA" (Natalya 
Polezhayeva), "KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA" (Vladislav Fronin), 
"IZVESTIYA" (first deputy chief editor Nikolay Bodnaruk) as well 
as the chairman of the state committee for the mass media, Boris 
Mironov, and the first secretary of the Moscow Journalists' 
Union, Ludmila Scherbina. 
  Prior to this, the association of publishers and chief 
editors, unions of journalists of Moscow and Russia, Fund for 
Protection of Glasnost and other journalist organizations sent a 
letter to the prime minister listing their demands for saving 
the Russian press from a crisis. 
  In particular, they demanded revising the government 
decision 
to recalculate the basic funds of printing, communications, pulp 
and paper and other cooperating industries, granting journalists 
the right to participate in the privatization of printing 
enterprises and other facilities, introducing subsidies for 
timely issuing of pre-paid editions, and lower taxes imposed on 
the mass media. 
  In their letter, journalists proposed the prime minister 
"immediately receive representatives from the press and 
journalist organizations." 

</TEXT>

