<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA Not To Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501173594 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Silence Again?"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] In the past few days a lot of 
questions from readers have been coming into our newspaper's 
editorial office: Will SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA support its 
colleagues' action? Even without this the newspaper was 
unlawfully closed down for almost three months, and subscribers 
failed to receive a great deal of important, true information 
about a whole period in the life of Russia and the world. 
Surely we will not be left without a newspaper again, they ask 
worriedly. 
  Although we fully share the undoubtedly just indignation of 
our journalist colleagues at the prevailing price chaos and 
bureaucratic chaos, we are nevertheless forced to say no to the 
collective protest action. We hold too dear the possibility -- 
recently infrequent -- of communicating with our readers, we 
have too much to say, we have too many lies to refute. For us, 
the SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA journalists, silence is a luxury we 
cannot afford. 
  We have our own score to settle with the present 
authorities, 
and it too is not small. No one intends to compensate for the 
losses to readers and the journalists' collectives which were 
brought about by the unlawful closure of the newspaper, and 
subscriptions to our newspapers are being hindered and blocked 
in every way at the mail offices. Every conceivable and 
inconceivable obstacle is placed on the path of every issue of 
SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA published. The situation is exacerbated many 
times by the fact that the editorial office's current account 
was unlawfully impounded literally until yesterday. Because of 
this we are not in a position to settle our accounts with our 
partners in the production and distribution of the newspaper in 
a timely fashion. 
  In the face of this, to be published, to get through to the 
reader, having penetrated the cordon of obstacles, means to 
conquer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

