<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Six Newspapers To Suspend Publication During Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501205894 Paris AFP in English 2047 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan 5 (AFP) -- Six Russian newspapers said 
Wednesday that they would suspend publication for one week from 
Monday, during US President Bill Clinton's visit, to protest 
against government restrictions on the press. 
  The shutdown, which had initially been threatened during a 
press conference Tuesday, was sparked by a November 25 
government decision that would cause a sixfold rise in newspaper 
production costs. 
  The newspapers consider this as the latest move to strangle 
Russia's emerging independent media, and blame the government 
for fighting to control the mass media rather than to guarantee 
freedom of the press. 
  The six politically diverse newspapers -- IZVESTIYA, 
KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA, ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI, MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS, 
MOSKOVSKAYA PRAVDA and VECHERNAYA MOCKVA -- will be shut down 
for at least one week from January 10, according to a decision 
by their editors. 
  Russian journalists' union president Vsevolod Bogdanov said 
that a majority of local and regional newspapers would also join 
the movement. 
  The editors said, however, that they would be willing to 
renounce the suspension if an immediate solution to their 
problem was found. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

