<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Program Set for Clinton Visit to Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601095794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0904 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yuriy Romantsov] </F>
  [Text] New York January 6 TASS -- Russian Deputy Foreign 
Minister Georgiy Mamedov who participated in the bilateral 
American- Russian political consultations in Washington, said 
the following on Thursday [6 January] in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS after their end. 
  "Our discussions," the deputy minister said, "were 
comprehensive and successful in all respects. Naturally, we 
concentrated on the programme of President Clinton's visit to 
Russia on the eve of the Russian-American summit to be held in 
Moscow between January 12 and 15." 
  According to Mamedov, the programme was agreed on all key 
issues. It can be said with certainty, he added, that 
preparations for the summit are progressing successfully. 
  Mamedov noted that the sides would focus on social and 
economic issues at the Moscow meeting and talks: progress of 
reforms in Russia and the economic situation in the world. 
  They will also discuss peace-making efforts, above all in 
such regions as Bosnia and Nagorno-Karabakh. The two sides 
attach much importance to strengthening the nuclear 
non-proliferation regime. 
  This issue will occupy an important place on the agenda. As 
for Russia, it discusses this question both with Americans and 
other countries. 
  The summit programme also includes bilateral relations: 
environmental control, air service, etc. 

</TEXT>

