<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details Given </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501181394 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1700 GMT 
5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The number of employees of the newly created Russian 
Federal Counterintelligence Service, including its territorial 
structures, will be approximately 75,000. In comparison with 
the Russian Ministry of Security, abolished in December, the 
number of personnel is being cut by 46 percent. Sergey 
Stepashin, first deputy head of the Federal Counterintelligence 
Service, reported this in an interview to INTERFAX. According 
to him, the new service will not have investigation and 
detention centers. It will not be fighting corruption, which is 
not characteristic of its functions. Such functions were 
formerly carried out by Ministry of Interior organs. The 
Lefortovo detention center where organizers of the 3-4 October 
events in Moscow are now being held is being transferred to the 
Ministry of Internal Affairs. All these changes were approved 
in the course of today's meeting in Moscow between the leaders 
of the Federal Counterintelligence Service and President Boris 
Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

