<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Service Will Have 75,000 Officers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601094694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0825 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By KRIM-PRESS correspondent Sergey Oleynik for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- The number of Russian 
counterintelligence officers will total 75,000 which is 46 per 
cent less than before the former Security Ministry was 
transformed into the Federal Counterintelligence Service, 
according to a spokesman of the service. 
  Aleksey Kondaurov told CRIME-PRESS on Thursday that all 
officers of the former Security Ministry will have to pass 
qualification tests before getting a new employment, however he 
denied that this would be a "personnel purge". 
  "If anyone is to be dismissed, this would be done only at 
his 
own request or in connection with retirement", he added. 
  The new provisions for the counterintelligence service, 
which 
were approved by the Russian president and to who it will 
directly report, entrust it with the struggle against all types 
of espionage - economic, political, military and scientific. 
  Besides, the service will fight terrorism and drug 
trafficking, according to Kondaurov who added that the service 
will no longer engage in activities alien to counterintelligence 
tasks. 
  The former Security Ministry anti-organised crime department 
was transferred to the Interior Ministry, while the 
investigation department became a part of the office of the 
Russian prosecutor general. The former KGB investigation prison 
in Lefortovo was also transferred to the Interior Ministry. 
  The service will consist of four major departments - 
counterintelligence, military counterintelligence, economic 
counterintelligence, terrorism and drug fighting, according to 
Kondaurov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

