<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Siberian Papers To Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601093794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 6 Jan 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0601093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Valeriy Yaroslavtsev report: "Siberians Support Central </F>
Newspapers' Editorial Offices"] 
  [Text] Krasnoyarsk -- For around two months now residents 
of Krasnoyarsk Kray and the republics of Khakasiya and Tuva have 
not read ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA. That is the length of time that it 
has not been printed by Krasnoyarsk's "Ofset" Production and 
Publishing Combine owing to lack of money to cover paper and 
printing costs. 
  This is a graphic example of what may happen to other 
Russian 
publications as a result of Russian Federation Government Decree 
No. 1233 on revaluing the capital stock at national economic 
enterprises. Krasnoyarsk newspapers have reprinted ahe Appeal 
from Russian press personnel and the chief editors of the 
leading central newspapers to V. Chernomyrdin, chairman of the 
Russian Federation Government. 
  The editors of leading Krasnoyarsk and certain rayon 
newspapers, as well as the "Ofset" Publishing House, have signed 
up to the appeal. As a sign of solidarity they are willing to 
stop publishing during the first "week of parliament" -- 11 
through 17 January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

