<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Military Plant Completes `Structural Reorganization' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601124994 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0601124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Vladimir Plotnikov and Vadim Telichev from Crimea; from </F>
the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] [Plotnikov] In the new year there are more thorough 
structural changes in store for industry in Ukraine and 
particularly in Crimea. This is the case, for example, at the 
former "Foton" production association in Simferopol, which used 
to provide services for the defense sector but which has now 
become a commercial science and production firm and is rapidly 
increasing its output of nontraditional goods. Those goods 
include microwave ovens, large-screen TV sets, 55-channel 
satellite TV receivers, and antennae. They are cheaper than 
their foreign equivalents and can be bought not for dollars but 
for Ukrainian coupons. Structural reorganization is a means of 
salvation for many other enterprises in conditions when there 
are no raw materials, demand for traditional goods has fallen, 
and the energy crisis has become extremely acute. The Crimean 
Supreme Soviet decree on an open economy regime in the peninsula 
offers good scope for this kind of reorganization. This decree 
will encourage the participation of foreign partners and 
investors in the development of a modern production industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

