<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Chairs Meeting of Public Order, Security Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601220294 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1500 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601220294 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Kazakh </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Sergey Tereshchenko today chaired a 
regular meeting of a group that was set up in accordance with a 
statute of President Nursultan Nazarbayev on raising 
responsibility of the state management body's officials over the 
state of discipline, public order, and security. It examined 
the issue of safe storage of weapons by the republican Armed 
Forces. As a check shows, more than 400 units of weapons were 
stolen or lost last year from military regiments. Among the 
weapons are 148 rifles and automatic machines [as received], 175 
revolvers, 46 grenade cup dischargers, and five machine-guns. A 
certain quantity of them have been returned. But still a large 
number of weapons are owned by criminals. Criminal cases have 
been initiated on all these facts. 
  The participants of the meeting strengthened the need for 
specifying a circle of people in the Armed Forces who will be 
held responsible for military arsenals. The session also 
discussed the aggravating criminal situation in Dzhambul Oblast. 
The level of crime solvency continues to worry us. Last year 
it did not exceed 52 percent. The Chu valley, with its hemp 
fields, has become a destabilizing factor. It has become a sort 
of a pilgrimage for drug addicts practically from all over the 
CIS. The session adopted recommendations aimed at radical 
improvement of the law enforcement bodies activities. It was 
decided to examine the issue of their realization over a period 
of four months. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

