<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Autonomies Urged To Align With Russia's Fundamental Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601161994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1345 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Experts in the local administration department of 
the Russian president called on Boris Yeltsin to set up a 
commission which would bring the constitutions of republics 
incorporated in Russia in line with the new Fundamental Law of 
the Russian Federation, the president's chief of staff Nikolay 
Medvedev told INTERFAX. 
  In his words, the experts found that numerous provisions of 
the recently adopted constitutions of Tatarstan, Bashkortostan 
and Tuva were inconsistent with Russia's Constitution. Twelve 
other republics, he said, still have old constitutions which are 
also inconsistent with the new Constitution of the Russian 
Federation. In particular, by its constitution Mordovia is a 
Soviet Socialist Republic. 
  Medvedev placed special emphasis on the fact that five newly 
established republics, Adygey, Altai, Ingushetia, 
Karachayevo-Cherkessia and Khakasia, do not have their own 
constitutions. The presidential chief of staff emphasized that, 
according to Article 72 of the Russian Constitution, the Russian 
Federation and its constituent parts would establish general 
principles of organizing systems of state authority and local 
government bodies. In numerous republics elections to the 
republican and local legislatures will be held shortly. In this 
light, the constitutions of the republics must as soon as 
possible be brought in line with the Fundamental Law of the 
Russian Federation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

