<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Not Sure He Will Remain in Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601173494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1653 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- Russian Deputy Prime 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin said he did not know if he would 
remain in the government after a new cabinet reshuffle. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Thursday, Shokhin said 
that 
a draft decree on the reorganisation of the government has been 
seen only by two people -- President Boris Yeltsin himself and 
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. "Neither I, nor other 
deputy prime ministers to whom I have spoken have not been 
involved in the work on a new structure of the government." 
  He pointed out that "this is not the best variant of 
reorganisation when deputy prime ministers are excluded from 
preparatory work." 
  Shoknin said that according to newspapers the number of 
federal ministers will be reduced and some state committees will 
be reorganised into ministries or other federal services. 
  Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said earlier 
today 
that the upcoming cabinet reshuffle will considerably reduce the 
number of ministers in the Federal Government. He said that 
"the number of ministers will be reduced sharply. There will be 
not more than 30 of them" in the government. He vowed that "the 
reduction will not hamper the government's work, but rather make 
it more efficient." 
  Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeyko said that "a 
decree on the reorganisation of the government will be signed by 
the president either today or tomorrow." 
  Speaking about his future, Shokhin said that if "the foreign 
economic bloc of the government 'dissolves' in the economic one, 
I will have to go to the State Duma" where he hopes to head its 
Foreign Affairs Committee, provided it will also handle foreign 
economic issues and CIS problems. "Though I have some other 
variants as well," he added. 
  He admitted that if Boris Fedorov is chosen to handle 
foreign 
economic issues in the government "it will be easier for me to 
express my politicised point of view on what he will be doing 
from the parliament rostrum." 

</TEXT>

