<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Appoints Yuriy Baturin National Security Aide </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601192694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1824 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: By Andrey </F>
Pershin, Andrey Petrovsky, and Vladimir Shishlin] 
  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin appointed Yuriy 
Baturin his national security aide Thursday, the president's 
press service reports. 
  Baturin, 44, Dr.Sc.(Law), a graduate of the Moscow Physic- 
Technical Institute, the Moscow Law Institute and the School of 
Journalism of Moscow University, has been the president's legal 
aide. 
  The introduction of the new position is in line with the 
Constitution, which calls for a strong presidency, the 
president's press secretary, Vyacheslav Kostikov, told 
Interfax's Vyacheslav Terekhov. 
  Furthermore, this is a natural continuation of the personnel 
policy in the post-Soviet period. Kostikov placed special 
emphasis on the fact that national security would be the 
responsibility of a civilian. 
  IF Note: According to a reliable source, Baturin was an 
adviser to Georgiy Shakhnazarov, an assistant to ex-USSR 
President Mikhail Gorbachev on foreign policy matters. Baturin 
was instrumental in drafting Yeltsin's key decisions last summer 
and autumn. In the opinion of a number of experts, he took part 
in working out in September of 1993 the presidential decree to 
dissolve the Supreme Soviet and Congress of People's Deputies 
and schedule new parliamentary elections. 
  On the threshold of the opening session of a new parliament, 
the president has taken a number of decisions concerning his 
close aides. On Tuesday, he decreed relieving Sergey Yushenkov, 
Mikhail Mityukov, Mikhail Poltoranin, and Ekaterina Lakhova of 
their duties because of their future parliamentary work. This 
has been reported by the president's information service. 
  Mityukov has up until now led the Presidential Committee on 
Legislative Initiatives. Poltoranin has been in charge of the 
Federal Information Center, Yushenkov has been Poltoranin's 
first deputy, and Lakhova has been a presidential adviser. 
  By yet another decree, Yeltsin has dismissed his envoy to 
the 
Maritime Territory, Butov. 
  Earlier, he sacked two advisers -- Sergey Stankevich (on 
political affairs) and Aleksey Yablokov (on environmental 
problems). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55271 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov005_b_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-005 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baturin Views Tasks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701130494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1139 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yuriy Baturin, 44, who was appointed Russian 
president's national security aide on January 6, told Interfax's 
Vyacheslav Terekhov that he was taken by surprise. "The 
presidential telephone buzzed. I took the receiver. Boris 
Nikolayevich (Yeltsin) says that he came to a conclusion that he 
needs a national security aide and that I should be that aide. 
I had a second to think it over." 
  In Baturin's words, he understood that "it would be 
inappropriate to refuse or ask questions. ... Not because he 
(Yeltsin) was harsh or anything but I felt he really needed it." 
  Baturin said that he had a first brief talk with the 
president about his new functions Thursday and "we'll have a 
more detailed conversation probably two or three days after the 
holidays (Russian Orthodox Christmas). 
  "I will be coordinating the activities of special services 
and supervision and decision making on everyday matters which 
must not encumber the president," Baturin explained. 
  He said that, in addition to foreign intelligence, services 
such as government communication, border guards and 
counterintelligence "which brings about the largest number of 
problems daily" report to the president. 
  Unlike the foreign intelligence which must present a report 
to the president once a week, there is no telling when a 
decision on counterintelligence will have to be made. "The 
president entrusts his national security aide with making a 
decision jointly with the chiefs of these services. I should 
naturally report to the president," Baturin said. 
  He will brief Yeltsin on the situation in general terms and 
report strategic issues on which the president alone has the 
right to make a decision. 
  Unlike the national Security Council which is a consultative 
body, the national security aide "will have to do business with 
special services daily." 
  Baturin said that a concept of national security existed 
which covered the activities of special services and defined the 
kinds of political and other activities which might harm 
Russia's national interests. 
  He told Interfax that following his appointment he had a 
talk 
with chiefs of the Federal Counterintelligence Service at their 
invitation. "Their attitude (towards establishing the position 
of a presidential national security aide) was very positive. 
They view this as an essentially new approach to security 
matters. We had a very good, productive, meaningful talk," 
Baturin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

