<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Likely To Vie for Federation Council Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0601131094 Moscow KURANTY in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK0601131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KURANTY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Kirill Varov report: "Shumeyko Remains a Favorite"] </F>
  [Text] Among the outgoing vice premiers in the government 
undergoing reformation Vladimir Shumeyko, who is considered by 
many a potential candidate in the future presidential elections, 
may receive the best possible "employment." It is known that 
Vladimir Filippovich does not intend to renounce the honor of 
running for the post of speaker of the upper parliament chamber 
-- the Federation Council -- if his candidacy is proposed by the 
president. It is another matter whether he has any real chances 
of getting a vote of confidence from his colleagues in the 
chamber. 
  The lineup of forces in the Federation Council appears to be 
far more enigmatic than in the State Duma, where partisan colors 
are much brighter and more definitive. In the Federation 
Council, on the other hand, according to preliminary estimates, 
Russia's Choice has six mandates, the communists about 12, while 
the bulk of the "senators," including almost 140 people, is not 
affiliated with any movement or bloc. Or rather they belong to 
the party of Russian bureaucracy, being officials of various 
ranks, and therefore it is quite natural that the great 
communicator Shumeyko, deprived of apparent extreme 
characteristics, has good chances of coming to terms with his 
colleagues in the vast Russian apparatus. Although, to be sure, 
there are various options.... 

</TEXT>

