<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin To Seek Vote of Confidence From Duma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0601165294 Paris AFP in English 1631 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0601165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan 6 (AFP) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin will seek a vote of confidence from the Duma, or 
lower house of parliament, when it meets next Tuesday [11 
January], Deputy Prime Minister Sergey Shakhray said Thursday. 
  He told reporters that the move "would help eliminate any 
misunderstanding between the government and the deputies." 
  Shakhray added that the 24 deputies belonging to his party, 
the Russia Unity and Accord Party that ran against the 
government-backed Russia's Choice party during the recent 
legislative elections, would give Chernomyrdin their vote of 
confidence. 
  He said that he expected a government reshuffle planned by 
President Boris Yeltsin to be a source of tension between the 
Kremlin and parliament, which has little say in the matter. 
  Shakhray, who may be targeted by the reshuffle according to 
local press reports, said he would not react "hysterically" if 
that were the case. 
  He said he plans to seek the presidency of the Duma despite 
the clear opposition of many of the political parties. 

</TEXT>

