<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Yet To Solve Accommodation, Procedure Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601142994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0601142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Yermolin report: "The Government Can Be </F>
Congratulated on Its New Home. But What of the New Russian 
Parliament?"] 
  [Text] Four days remain until the Russian Federation 
Federal Assembly starts its work. It seems that this uncommon 
event in the country's life will be marked by the last-minute 
rush which is traditional for projects due for completion. In 
the new parliament's press center we were told that the venue 
for the first session is still unclear: either the Kremlin or 
the building which until the well-known events belonged to 
mayor's office. There is also total obscurity in respect of the 
standing orders. There is no question of agreed candidacies for 
the speaker and his deputies -- which, however, is not a drama 
in itself. We have been told by the Central Electoral 
Commission that four days before the State Duma begins its work 
the lists of deputies from parties and associations are still 
being sorted out. 
  Objectively speaking, the procedure for finishing such an 
important "project due for completion" has been messed up by the 
holidays, and there is also the effect of the "unraveling 
government" -- part of it has gone to apartments at the White 
House, and part has resigned in connection with the reform of 
government structures. The telephones -- not to mention 
continuity -- have been cut off. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

