<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation's Communist Parties Start To Unite </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601152394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1404 
GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 6 January -- A Union of Communist Parties 
(Roskomsoyuz) ["Russian Communist Union"] has, in effect, come 
into being in Russia. This statement was made to journalists 
today by Aleksey Prigarin, leader of the Union of Communists, 
who talked about the results of the meeting of the ruling bodies 
of all-Russia communist parties, held at the end of last year. 
The meeting, he pointed out, proclaimed the start of the 
consolidation of the previously uncoordinated and extremely 
small All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks), the Russian 
Communist Workers' Party, the Russian Party of Communists, the 
Union of Communists, and the Leninist Platform in the CPRF 
[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]. 
  According to Aleksey Prigarin, the basis for the 
consolidation of these forces was provided by their common 
stance on the December elections and referendum. 
  Particular attention was devoted by the news conference 
organizers to an exposition of their view on the stance adopted 
by the CPRF leadership, given the conditions actually existing 
in Russia. As Aleksey Prigarin put it, the Communist Party of 
the Russian Federation, headed by Gennadiy Zyuganov, had, in 
effect, adopted social-democratic positions. Aleksey Prigarin 
decribed the emergent Union's relations with the CPRF as 
"amicably hostile." 

</TEXT>

