<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray's Party Concerned Over State Duma's Future </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601172194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1552 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- The Party of Russian Unity 
and Accord supports the position of the Inter-regional 
Association of Independent Deputies on the election of the State 
Duma leadership. 
  Party leader Sergey Shakhray, who is also Russian vice-prime 
minister, told a news conference in Moscow on Thursday that 
there have been attempts by large election blocs to predetermine 
the fate of the State Duma behind the back of the majority of 
deputies. He stressed that the Party of Russian Unity and 
Accord is ready for forming a broad coalition in the Duma "at 
least on the basis of a common approach towards the principle of 
election of the Duma chairman." This would ensure the equality 
of all deputies, he added. 
  Independent deputies of the State Duma warned on Wednesday 
that large election blocs are seeking to gain control of the 
State Duma. 
  A statement issued by the Inter-Regional Association of 
Independent Deputies of the lower house of the Federal Assembly 
suggested reforming the house factions not only by the principle 
of their party orientation, but also by other principles. It 
also proposed forming ruling bodies of the house on a parity 
basis. The deputies believe that every candidate should be 
elected by secret ballot. 
  They said that deputies of the State Duma chairman should be 
elected on a parity basis: One from the election blocs and the 
other from individual constituencies. Additionally, the house 
procedural regulations should be based not on a party principle, 
but on the principle of multi-factionalism which takes into 
account the interests of the whole deputy corps. As for the 
procedural regulations they should not violate the constitution 
or contradict the voters's will, the deputies said. 
  Shakhray said his party believes that the government should 
raise the question of confidence in itself in the State Duma. 
This would be a "forestalling step by the Cabinet of Ministers 
to promote interaction between the government and the 
parliament." In any case "we will support Viktor Chernomyrdin 
as prime minister," Shakhray added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

