<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Campaign Funding Affair Seen Not Imperiling Zhirinovskiy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0601125094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK0601125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Leontyev commentary: "Elections Financing: "None </F>
Will be the Wiser?"] 
  [Text] Today is the deadline for submitting to the Central 
Electoral Commission documents about the sources of financing 
for the election campaigns of deputies and electoral blocs. 
While some blocs will have no difficulty providing the 
documents, a sizable number of deputies and parties have nothing 
to line up. One need not be surprised at a situation where, for 
example, the special account of "Zhirinovskiy's party" will show 
"zero" both in income and outgo in addition to the 50 million 
rubles issued by the Central Electoral Commission. Whereas the 
LDPR [Liberal Democratic Party of Russia] had to disclose this 
account if only to receive the government subsidy for television 
in the election campaign, for many deputies doing so simply made 
no sense. 
  The fact is that the election regulation is only very 
particular about the use of special election accounts, whereas 
no one proscribes the use of any other accounts belonging to 
these persons and parties or to totally extraneous ones. This 
is something that virtually all blocs and deputies did. More, 
the extremely detailed rules on the use of special accounts 
envision no concrete sanctions for their violation. Therefore, 
neither the use of foreign sources nor the receipt of state 
funds to finance an election campaign can really endanger one's 
deputy seat thus received. 
  However, accountants for newspapers, radio stations and, 
first and foremost, television have all the documents in payment 
for ads and air time. The content of these documents is no 
commercial secret or even simply confidential information. No 
one is preventing television and the newspapers from publishing 
the sizes and sources of payment of these election campaign 
expenses -- and thereby to fulfill their moral and civic duty 
since the poorly compiled election regulations leave society at 
sea about who finances today's people's choices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55289 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov005_b_94025" </HT>


