<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Makers Plan Shift to Fusion Reactor Project </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501162594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By D. Kokko and V. Gonchar from St. Petersburg's "Severnyy </F>
Zavod" Production Association; from the "Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] [Kokko over video of missiles] A couple of years 
ago TV crews could not even dream of gaining access to this 
enterprise. For many years the "Severnyy Zavod" Production 
Association produced nothing but missiles for air defense 
systems. Nowadays the need for conversion is felt even here, 
although views differ on how to tackle the problems which have 
arisen. 
  According to the plant's director, owing to shortsighted 
government policy Russia currently has no real chance of 
entering the world market in defense weapon systems. Production 
is declining, but we simply must preserve our high-tech 
facilities. This gave birth to the project to build a spherical 
Tokamak. Previously this argon chamber was used to make wings 
for missiles. Now it is used to make titanium ice-axes for 
Norway. 
  However, recently a project was drawn up in cooperation with 
physicists from the Ioffe Institute to build a spherical Tokamak 
for research in the field of thermonuclear reactions. 
Theoretical studies have already been carried out and a 
1:10-scale model has been built. If it proves possible to 
translate the project to build a spherical Tokamak into reality, 
Russia will undoubtedly take up a leading position in the world 
in the sphere of thermonuclear fusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

