<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Gamsakhurdia's Reported Death </TI></H3>
<H4>   Burial With Honor Recommended </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601190494 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1445 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone report by IPRINDA correspondent Zurab Dvali from </F>
Tbilisi] 
  [Text] Today is exactly two years since the first popularly 
elected Georgian president, Zviad Gamsakhurdia, together with 
about 50 of his followers, escaped at dawn from his bunker in 
the government house, surrounded by the opposition, and fled 
from the republic. It is 6 January again -- this time 1994, and 
again the destiny of this man is at the center of attention of 
virtually all the local and foreign media. 
  An official delegation lead by Chechen Republic Vice 
President Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev arrived in Tbilisi late last 
night. According to information we have, the guests intend to 
investigate all the details connected with Zviad Gamsakhurdia's 
death -- along with examining a whole range of economic, trade, 
and other issues. They have also passed on to the head of the 
Georgian state a request made by the Georgian ex-president's 
wife Manana to allow the body of her husband to be buried in his 
homeland. She means the family cemetery in the grounds of the 
house in Tbilisi that belonged to the ex- president's father. 
Eduard Shevardnadze has declined this request. However, some 
sources claim that the funeral could take place in the 
Gamsakhurdia family home village in western Georgia. 
  It also become known today that Chechen President Dzhokhar 
Dudayev has issued an official statement in which he indicates 
that Zviad Gamsakhurdia should be buried in his homeland with 
all the honors that befit the first president of Georgia. In 
connection with this, Dudayev appealed to democratic circles of 
Russia, asking them to put pressure on official Tbilisi. 
  At the same time, the question of whether Gamsakhurdia has 
really shot himself still remains open. At any rate, a doubt 
about this version of events was expressed not only by 
representatives of the special services who, in one way or 
another, were closely following the ex-president's activities 
all this time, but also people who were personally close to 
Zviad Gamsakhurdia. Anyway, the fact remains -- a man whose 
name was connected at first with the best hopes and aspirations 
of the Georgian people, and who later was accused of every 
mortal sin and proclaimed a chief ideologist of provincial 
fascism and a traitor, is no more. 
  As the saying goes, speak no ill of the dead. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55312 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov005_s_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-005 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Gamsakhurdia's Reported Death </TI></H3>
<H4>   Commentary on Death </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601225994 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601225994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Moscow Russian Television Network in 
Russian at 2030 GMT on 6 January broadcasts an eight minute 
commentary on the report of the death of former Georgian 
President Zviad Gamsakhurdia. 
  The program interspersed its own commentary with the 
reactions and views of interviewees. It did not reveal 
additional information about the circumstances surrounding 
Gamsakhurdia's reported death, nor did it offer further 
confirmations of existing reports. 
  Valerian Advadze, Georgian ambassador to Russia, who was 
interviewed in the Georgian embassy in Moscow, said that he, 
like his colleagues in Tbilisi, had learned about Gamsakhurdia's 
death from the Russian media. Advadze expressed doubt that 
Gamsakhurdia had committed suicide: "With his character he would 
have been unable to kill himself; he would not have had the 
courage." He said he thought it more likely that Gamsakhurdia 
was killed by one of his own entourage. 
  Asked by the announcer whether Gamsakhurdia's death, if it 
had taken place, would be advantageous to the Georgian 
leadership, Advadze replied: "I can firmly state that it would 
have no influence and no significance for either the leadership 
or the people, because he had already shown himself up once and 
for all, and had been dead politically for a long time already. 
There was no chance that he could make another expedition to 
Tbilisi, like the one he launched recently." 
  Continuing his commentary, the announcer expressed the view 
that Gamsakhurdia's death would affect Russian interests, 
referring to Gamsakhurdia's links with Abkhazia and Chechnya. 
However, V. E. Yegoshkin, acting director of the Transcaucasus 
department of the Russian Foreign Ministry, told the program 
that Russia's relations with Georgia did not depend on who was 
in power: "Our relations with Georgia and its people do not 
depend on who holds political power in that country. That is 
the internal affairs of the Georgians themselves, and Russia 
sees no point in interfering in Georgia's internal affairs." 
  Finally, the commentator recapped the latest controversy 
over 
Gamsakhurdia's place of burial, adding: "So one way or another, 
almost everyone is ready to bury him. If he is still alive, it 
will be difficult for him to find his place again in this 
rapidly changing world." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

