<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Gamsakhurdia's Reported Death </TI></H3>
<H4>   Chechen President Offers Groznyy Site </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601182194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1726 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601182194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev has offered Zviad 
Gamsakhurdia's relatives to bury him in Groznyy. According to 
Interfax sources, Dudayev believes that as Georgia's first 
legally elected president, Gamsakhurdia must be buried with all 
honors. 
  Groznyy's mayor's office told Interfax that requests were 
being made for naming a street in Groznyy after Gamsakhurdia. 
Groznyy's First Vice Mayor Sayid-Magomed Inorkayev said that 
Gamsakhurdia's name would be given to one of the city's most 
beautiful streets. He also said that the city administration 
was ready to organize a funeral ceremony in Groznyy. 
  Earlier, Gamsakhurdia's wife Manana had told Interfax that 
her husband must be buried in Tbilisi, in the courtyard of his 
house, near his father's grave. She doubts, however, that the 
Georgian officials will allow her to do so. 

</TEXT>

