<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Critical of Ardzinba's Remarks on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601175194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1738 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tbilisi January 6 GIA-TASS -- The Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs of Georgia today issued a statement criticizing 
Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba for his announcement broadcast 
by radio that he felt "pretty skeptical" about the 
Georgian-Abkhaz consultations scheduled for January 11 in Geneva. 
  According to the Georgian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, these 
words of Ardzinba "testify not only to his skepticism but also 
to his intention to poison the atmosphere around the forthcoming 
talks and even to disrupt them as far as possible". 
  This assumption is borne out by Ardzinba's reiterated 
statement that "Abkhazia is no longer part of Georgia" and that 
"the question now is about signing an agreement between Abkhazia 
and Georgia as two equal parties". 
  A second round of consultations between Georgia and Abkhazia 
is scheduled to begin in Geneva on January 11. "The delegation 
from Georgia has been instructed to draw up, jointly with the 
Abkhaz delegation, a framework for the full-scale settlement in 
Abkhazia, which can be used as the basis of a resolution to be 
adopted by the United Nations Security Council," the Georgian 
statement said. 
  "Only a document recognised and guaranteed by the 
international community can ensure the restoration of peace in 
Abkhazia," the Georgian Ministry of Foreign Affairs said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

